## 5. Compatibility & Setup Guide

- Best Blade Matches
    - Outer Carbon: Great for high-level players who want maximum speed and are comfortable managing the high throw (e.g., Viscaria, Nittaku Acoustic Carbon).
    - Inner Carbon: The sweet spot. Balances the rubber's catapult with excellent dwell and control (e.g., Nittaku Hurricane Pro 3, W968).
    - All-Wood: Works beautifully on stiff 7-ply woods (e.g., Clipper) to provide a linear, solid backbone.
    - Mismatch Cases: Overly flexible 5-ply woods. The rubber is already bouncy and heavy; a flexy blade might make the setup feel too unpredictable and bottom-heavy.

- Forehand vs. Backhand Recommendation
    - Forehand: Exceptional choice. It supports heavy power looping and mid-distance rallies perfectly.
    - Backhand: Great for advanced attackers who play active backhand loops. May be too fast and catapulty for players who rely on passive backhand blocking.

